<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Learn how to make authentic Spanish sangria with this easy sangria recipe.Â  It only takes a few minutes to prep, it&#8217;s easy to customize with your favorite wine and fruit, and it&#8217;s great for entertaining a crowd!</em></p>
<p><img data-pin-title="Sangria" class="aligncenter wp-image-59010 size-full" title="LOVE this easy sangria recipe! It only takes 10 minutes to prep, it's customizable with whatever kind of wine or fruit you have on hand, and it's always a crowd fave. Perfect for easy summer entertaining! | gimmesomeoven.com #sangria #cocktail #drink #summer #spain #recipe" src="http://www.gimmesomeoven.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Authentic-Spanish-Sangria-Recipe-3-1.jpg" alt="Sangria Recipe" width="1392" height="2089" data-pin-description="LOVE this easy sangria recipe! It only takes 10 minutes to prep, it's customizable with whatever kind of wine or fruit you have on hand, and it's always a crowd fave. Perfect for easy summer entertaining! | gimmesomeoven.com #sangria #cocktail #drink #summer #spain #recipe" srcset="https://www.gimmesomeoven.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Authentic-Spanish-Sangria-Recipe-3-1.jpg 1392w, https://www.gimmesomeoven.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Authentic-Spanish-Sangria-Recipe-3-1-1100x1651.jpg 1100w, https://www.gimmesomeoven.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Authentic-Spanish-Sangria-Recipe-3-1-768x1153.jpg 768w, https://www.gimmesomeoven.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Authentic-Spanish-Sangria-Recipe-3-1-1391x2088.jpg 1391w, https://www.gimmesomeoven.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Authentic-Spanish-Sangria-Recipe-3-1-320x480.jpg 320w" sizes="(max-width: 1392px) 100vw, 1392px" /></p>
<p>Ever since we moved to Barcelona, I&#8217;ve been getting lots of requests for an authentic Spanish sangria recipe here on the blog.Â  But as it turns out &#8212; I&#8217;m so sorry to break it to you &#8212; locals here don&#8217;t really drink sangria!</p>
<p>I know, it was a major shocker to us too when we moved here.Â  But if you glance around a restaurant here in Spain, it&#8217;s almost always just the tourists who are the ones with pitchers of sangria on their tables.Â  When locals here are craving a cold drink, they usually opt instead for a glass ofÂ <em>vermut</em> (here in Catalonia) orÂ <em>sidra</em> (in Asturias) orÂ <em>tinto de veranoÂ </em>(wine with lemon soda down in the south) or <em>k</em><em>alimotxo</em> (wine with Coke in the Basque country).Â  Granted, Spaniards do proudly take the credit for sangria, although the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sangria">details of its origins are murky</a>.Â  And my Spanish friends also made sure to note as I was writing this post that they <em>do</em> occasionally make a batch of sangria at home in the summertime, especially when they&#8217;re looking for a cheap and easy way to provide drinks for a crowd.Â  But in the entire time that we&#8217;ve been living in Spain, we&#8217;ve been served sangria a grand total ofÂ <em>one</em> time.Â  So&#8230;there&#8217;s that.Â ðŸ˜…</p>
<p>Still, even if it is admittedly more of a touristy thing here, I love making sangria this time of year!Â  I&#8217;ve long said that it&#8217;s my go-to cocktail for summer entertaining, especially since it&#8217;s so easy to make (less than 10 minutes or prep), relatively affordable (and a great use for inexpensive wine), completely customizable with your favorite ingredients (hello, summer fruit season), and always tastes <em>so</em> light and refreshing andÂ summery (y-u-m).Â  Oh and bonus, it&#8217;s easy to prep hours in advance and always looks so vibrant and gorgeous in a pitcher.Â  And in my experience, it&#8217;sÂ <em>always</em> a hit with a crowd.</p>
<p>So if you are interested in learning how to make authentic sangria, I thought I would continue our Spanish recipe series today and show you the way that it&#8217;s prepared here in Spain!</p>
