<h2 style="text-align: center;">Spanish Sangria Ingredients:</h2>
<p>If you ask bartenders here in Spain how to make sangria, they will be the first to tell you that &#8212;Â technically &#8212; there is no standard way to make sangria.Â  It&#8217;s really just a wine punch, made with seasonal fruit, sweetener, a good splash of brandy, and possibly something fizzy added in.Â  But beyond that, the details are 100% up to you!Â  I&#8217;ve included lots of tips below for how to customize your own sangria recipe.Â  But as a starting place, here are the sangria ingredients that are used most commonly here in Spain:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Spanish red wine:Â </strong>I mean, as <a href="http://www.gimmesomeoven.com/spanish-wine-101/">the world&#8217;s third largest wine producer</a>, Spaniards would <em>insist</em> that you choose a decent Spanish red for your sangria.Â  (Rioja wine is the popular choice, which typically features garnacha and/or tempranillo grapes.)Â  But no need to splurge on an expensive bottle.Â  Sangria is the perfect way to gussy up any inexpensive or leftover wine that you might have on hand.</li>
<li><strong>Brandy:Â </strong>This is the spirit most commonly added to Spanish sangria recipes.Â  But if you don&#8217;t have any on hand, feel free to sub in cognac or orange liqueur instead.</li>
<li><strong>Fresh chopped fruit:Â </strong>The standard three you will see most often in Spain are oranges, lemons and green apples.Â  But as I mention below, feel free to also add in any extra juicy fruit that you might have on hand.</li>
<li><strong>Cinnamon stick:Â </strong>Yep, cinnamon!Â  This was a fun surprise moving to Spain &#8212; there&#8217;s almost always a cinnamon stick floating in every pitcher of sangria here.</li>
<li><strong>Sweetener:Â </strong>Feel free to add as much sweetener to your sangria you would like.Â  Sugar or brown sugar is standard here in Spain (melted into a simple syrup, with equal parts boiling water and sugar).Â  But feel free to use maple syrup or honey for a natural alternative.</li>
<li><strong>Bubbles:Â </strong>Totally up to you if you would like to make your sangria a bit fizzy!Â  I prefer mine flat, but feel free to top your glasses off with a light soda (such as Sprite, La Casera or ginger ale) or sparkling water just before serving if you would like.</li>
</ul>
